            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Retention Rate = ((Customers at end of period - New customers during period) / Customers at start of period) x 100. Example: Starting with 1,000 customers, gaining 200 new ones, and ending with 1,050 total gives 85% retention — 850 of the original 1,000 stayed.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between retention rate and churn rate?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>They are inverses of each other. A 92% retention rate equals 8% churn. Both describe the same underlying data from different perspectives. Use whichever your stakeholders prefer; just stay consistent in reporting.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Should I focus on retention or acquisition first?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
